Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into 1⁄2-inch-thick wedges. Halve, peel, and finely dice @yellow onion{1}. Halve @potato buns{2}. Thinly slice @roma tomato{1} into rounds.

Cut @broccoli florets{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary.

> Save potatoes for another use.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @?cooking oil{}, @garlic powder{3/4%tsp} (1 1⁄2 tsp for 4 servings), @salt{pinch}, and @pepper{pinch}.

> You'll use the rest of the garlic powder in the next step.

Roast on top rack until browned and crisp, ~{20-25%minutes}.

> Swap in broccoli for potatoes; roast 15-18 minutes.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine @white wine vinegar{5%tsp}, 1 TBSP onion (2 TBSP for 4 servings), @sugar{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4), and a pinch of @salt{}.

In a separate small bowl, combine @ketchup{2%tbsp}, @sour cream{2%tbsp}, @dijon mustard{2%tsp}, remaining @garlic powder{1/4%tsp}, and @sugar{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4).

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tbsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add remaining onion; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and softened, ~{5-7%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Transfer to a #plate{}.

While onion cooks, form @ground beef{10%ounce} into two patties (four patties for 4 servings), each slightly wider than a burger bun. Season generously with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Once onion is transferred to a plate, heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add patties and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

In the last ~{1-2%minutes} of cooking, top each patty with @cheddar cheese{1/2%cup}; cover pan to melt cheese.

While cheese melts, toast buns until golden brown.

Stir pickled onion (draining first) into bowl with special sauce.

Fill toasted buns with patties, griddled onion, tomato, and special sauce. Divide burgers between plates; serve with potato wedges and any remaining sauce on the side for dipping.